  <subsection permid="WEP">
    <title>Writing a Slope-Intercept Equation Given a Graph</title>
    <p permid="Ccr">
      We can write a linear equation in slope-intercept form based on its graph.
      We need to be able to calculate the line's slope and see its <m>y</m>-intercept.
    </p>

    <exercise permid="XoJ">
      <webwork >
      <setup>

            <pg-code>
                for my $i(0,1){
                $gr[$i]=init_graph(-2,-2,8,10,axes=>[0,0],grid=>[10,12],size=>[240,240]);
                $gr[$i]->moveTo(0,6);
                $gr[$i]->arrowTo(8,2,'blue',1);
                $gr[$i]->moveTo(0,6);
                $gr[$i]->arrowTo(-2,7,'blue',1);
                $gr[$i]->lb('reset');
                for my$j(-1..7){$gr[$i]->lb(new Label($j,-0.1,$j,'black','center','top','large'));};
                for my$j(-1..9){$gr[$i]->lb(new Label(-0.1,$j,$j,'black','right','middle','large'));};
                };
                $gr[1]->lb(new Label(0.1,6.1,'(0,6)','black','left','bottom','large'));
                $gr[1]->lb(new Label(3.9,3.9,'(4,4)','black','right','top','large'));
                $gr[1]->moveTo(0,6);
                $gr[1]->lineTo(4,6,'black',1);
                $gr[1]->arrowTo(4,4,'black',1);
                $gr[1]->lb(new Label(4,6.1,'4 - 0 = 4','black','right','bottom','small'));
                $gr[1]->lb(new Label(4.5,5,'4 - 6 = -2','black','left','middle','small'));
                Context()->operators->set(
                '+'=>{class=>'bizarro::BOP::add',isCommand=>1},
                '-'=>{class=>'bizarro::BOP::subtract',isCommand=>1},
                );
                parser::Assignment->Allow;
                Context()->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                $eq=Formula("y=-1/2x+6");
                $ev=$eq->cmp(checker=>sub{
                my($co,$st,$aH)=@_;
                return 0 if$aH->{isPreview}||$co!=$st;
                $st=$aH->{student_formula};
                $co=$co->{original_formula} if defined $co->{original_formula};
                $st=Formula("$st");$co=Formula("$co");
                return 0 unless($co==$st);
                Context()->flags->set(bizarroAdd=>1,bizarroSub=>1);
                delete $co->{test_values},$st->{test_values};
                Value->Error("Your answer is an equation for this line, but it is not in simplified slope-intercept form")unless(($co==$st)or($st==$co));
                Context()->flags->set(bizarroAdd=>0,bizarroSub=>0);
                return 1;
                })->withPostFilter(sub{my$ans=shift;
                $ans->{ans_message}="An equation for a line in slope-intercept form should start with 'y='"
                if $ans->{ans_message} eq "The left side of an assignment must be a variable or function";
                return $ans;
                });
            </pg-code>
      </setup>
      <statement>
        <p permid="IWW">
          Use the graph to write an equation of the line in slope-intercept form.
        </p>

        <sidebyside permid="yLZ" widths="40%">
          <image permid="GqL" pg-name="$gr[0]" />
        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="pef">
          <var name="$eq" evaluator="$ev" width="20"/>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="CEU">
        <p permid="EIC">
          On the line,
          pick two points with easy-to-read integer coordinates so that we can calculate slope.
          It doesn't matter which two points we use;
          the slope will be the same.
        </p>

        <sidebyside permid="eTi" widths="40%">
          <image pg-name="$gr[1]" />
        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="kPL">
          Using the slope triangle, we can calculate the line's slope:
          <me permid="TaC">
            \text{slope}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-2}{4}=-\frac{1}{2}\text{.}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p permid="QWU">
          From the graph, we can see the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,6)</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="xed">
          With the slope and <m>y</m>-intercept found,
          we can write the line's equation:
          <me permid="zhL">
            y=-\frac{1}{2}x+6\text{.}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
